The <b>Lavender Waxbill</b> (<i>Estrilda caerulescens</i>) is a common species of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Estrildid_finch" title="Estrildid finch">estrildid finch</a> native to Central Africa and successfully introduced on <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hawaii_(island)" title="Hawaii (island)">Hawai'i</a>. It has an estimated global extent of occurrence of 620,000&nbsp;km².
It is found in subtropical/ tropical (lowland) dry shrubland habitats in <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benin" title="Benin">Benin</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Burkina_Faso" title="Burkina Faso">Burkina Faso</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cameroon" title="Cameroon">Cameroon</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_African_Republic" title="Central African Republic">Central African Republic</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chad" title="Chad">Chad</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C%C3%B4te_d%27Ivoire" title="Côte d'Ivoire" class="mw-redirect">Côte d'Ivoire</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gambia" title="Gambia" class="mw-redirect">Gambia</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ghana" title="Ghana">Ghana</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guinea" title="Guinea">Guinea</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guinea-Bissau" title="Guinea-Bissau">Guinea-Bissau</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liberia" title="Liberia">Liberia</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mali" title="Mali">Mali</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Niger" title="Niger">Niger</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nigeria" title="Nigeria">Nigeria</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Senegal" title="Senegal">Senegal</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sudan" title="Sudan">Sudan</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Togo" title="Togo">Togo</a> &amp; <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/USA" title="USA" class="mw-redirect">USA</a> (breeding). The status of the species is evaluated as <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Least_Concern" title="Least Concern">Least Concern</a>.
Origin and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phylogeny" title="Phylogeny" class="mw-redirect">phylogeny</a> has been obtained by Antonio Arnaiz-Villena et al.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> Estrildinae may have originated in India and dispersed thereafter (towards Africa and Pacific Ocean habitats).
